"Van Groenigen K.-J., Six J., Hungate B.A., De Graaff M.-A., Van Breemen N., Van Kessel C.","Element interactions limit soil carbon storage",2006,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","103","17",,"6571","6574",,,10.1073/pnas.0509038103,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33646232989&partnerID=40&md5=145fab89eecbfccf20dce4b6a03fc1b6","Department of Plant Sciences, University of California, One Shields Avenue, Davis, CA 95616, United States; Laboratory for Soil Science and Geology, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 37, 6700 AA, Wageningen, Netherlands; Department of Biological Sciences and Merriam-Powell Center for Environmental Research, Northern Arizona University, P.O. Box 5640, Flagstaff, AZ 86011, United States","Van Groenigen, K.-J., Department of Plant Sciences, University of California, One Shields Avenue, Davis, CA 95616, United States, Laboratory for Soil Science and Geology, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 37, 6700 AA, Wageningen, Netherlands; Six, J., Department of Plant Sciences, University of California, One Shields Avenue, Davis, CA 95616, United States; Hungate, B.A., Department of Biological Sciences and Merriam-Powell Center for Environmental Research, Northern Arizona University, P.O. Box 5640, Flagstaff, AZ 86011, United States; De Graaff, M.-A., Department of Plant Sciences, University of California, One Shields Avenue, Davis, CA 95616, United States, Laboratory for Soil Science and Geology, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 37, 6700 AA, Wageningen, Netherlands; Van Breemen, N., Laboratory for Soil Science and Geology, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 37, 6700 AA, Wageningen, Netherlands; Van Kessel, C., Department of Plant Sciences, University of California, One Shields Avenue, Davis, CA 95616, United States","Rising levels of atmospheric CO2 are thought to increase C sinks in terrestrial ecosystems. The potential of these sinks to mitigate CO 2 emissions, however, may be constrained by nutrients. By using metaanalysis, we found that elevated CO2 only causes accumulation of soil C when N is added at rates well above typical atmospheric N inputs. Similarly, elevated CO2 only enhances N2 fixation, the major natural process providing soil N input, when other nutrients (e.g., phosphorus, molybdenum, and potassium) are added. Hence, soil C sequestration under elevated CO2 is constrained both directly by N availability and indirectly by nutrients needed to support N2 fixation. © 2006 by The National Academy of Sciences of the USA.","Global climate change; N2 fixation; Soil organic matter","carbon; carbon dioxide; molybdenum; nitrogen; phosphorus; potassium; soil organic matter; article; atmosphere; carbon dioxide fixation; cell interaction; climate change; ecosystem; fertilization; global climate; land biome; nitrogen fixation; plant growth; priority journal; soil analysis; stoichiometry; Carbon; Carbon Dioxide; Ecosystem; Greenhouse Effect; Nitrogen; Nitrogen Fixation; Plants; Soil",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; carbon, 7440-44-0; molybdenum, 7439-98-7; nitrogen, 7727-37-9; phosphorus, 7723-14-0; potassium, 7440-09-7; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Nitrogen, 7727-37-9; Soil",,,,"Schimel, D.S., (1995) Glob. Change Biol., 1, pp. 77-91; Mooney, H.A., Drake, B.G., Luxmoore, R.J., Oechel, W.C., Pitelka, L.F., (1991) Bioscience, 41, pp. 96-104; Gifford, R.M., (1994) Aunt. J. Plant Physiol., 21, pp. 1-15; Hungate, B.A., Dukes, J.S., Shaw, R., Luo, Y., Field, C.B., (2003) Science, 302, pp. 1512-1513; Rastetter, E.B., Ågren, G.I., Shaver, G.R., (1997) Ecol. Appl., 7, pp. 444-460; Cannell, M.G.R., Thornley, J.H.M., (1998) Glob. Change Biol., 4, pp. 431-442; Galloway, J.N., Dentener, F.J., Capone, D.G., Boyer, E.W., Howarth, R.W., Seitzinger, S.P., Asner, G.P., Holland, E.A., (2004) Biogeochemistty, 70, pp. 153-226; Zanetti, S., Hartwig, U.A., Luscher, A., Hebeisen, T., Frehner, M., Fischer, B.U., Hendrey, G.R., Nosberber, J., (1996) Plant Physi